MEASLES - INDONESIA (ALOR): REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Wed 3 Nov 2004
From: Andrew Jeremijenko <Andrew.Jeremijenko@vico.co.id>

[The following information has been received from Dr. Andrew Jeremijenko,
an Australian GP with an interest in the epidemiology of measles, who has
worked for 6 years in Indonesia. - Mod.CP]
The Jakarta Post reported, on Wed 3 Nov 2004, that a health official had
stated that 26 children under the age of 5 had died from a virulent measles
outbreak on the remote island of Alor, in East Nusa Tenggara, during the
past two weeks. "As small children lacked immunity, without treatment,
they could die after 3 days of exposure."
The Kupang Post reported, on Tue 2 Nov 2004, a "strange virus kills 26 Alor
children," and went on to say that 226 other people had been affected in
the villages. The diagnosis is not certain but is thought to be measles,
based on the description of the symptoms, including fever, cough, runny
nose, and a rash. However, the doctor stated that, if the children improve,
the symptoms are not similar to measles. "Namun setelah sembuh tidak ada
gejala pos morbiliti berupa bekas bintik-bintak hitam di kulit." I believe
this means that there are black lesions on the skin. Nusa Tenggara Timur
(NTT) is 90 percent Christian, and birds, pigs, and humans in these remote
islands often live in close proximity. Much of Indonesia is predominantly
Muslim, so pigs are not in close proximity with humans, so I believe it may
be beneficial to obtain further information about this outbreak.
--
Dr. Andrew Jeremijenko
VICO Medical advisor and NAMRU2 Flu surveillance project
MBBS, MAE, CertHEd, FRACGP CertHSM, MHA
<Andrew.Jeremijenko@vico.co.id>
[Dr. Jeremijenko comments that the severity of the illness is not unusual
for 3rd world measles. However, with the rapid deaths, and with some of the
symptoms mentioned, he would like to see this outbreak more thoroughly
investigated, and other possible diagnoses considered, such as (avian)
influenza or a hemorrhagic fever. Further information and clarification of
the diagnosis from informed sources in the region would be welcomed.
The full text of The Jakarta Post article of 3 Nov 2004 is given below. -
Mod.CP]
