[2]
Date: Wed 3 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Jakarta Post, Wed 3 Nov 2004 [edited]
<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Jakarta Post, Wed 3 Nov 2004 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailheadlines.asp?fileid=20041103.@03">promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Jakarta Post, Wed 3 Nov 2004 [edited]
<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Jakarta Post, Wed 3 Nov 2004 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailheadlines.asp?fileid=20041103.@03&irec=2>

Indonesia: 26 children die in measles outbreak in Alor
-----------------------------------------------
26 children, all under 5 years old, have died from a virulent measles
outbreak on the remote island of Alor, in East Nusa Tenggara, during the
past 2 weeks, a health official says. More than 200 other children are sick
with the virus in the villages of East Mataru, Taman Mataru, and Kamafui,
with 4 in a critical condition, local health office head Paul S. Manumpil
told The Jakarta Post on Tuesday [2 Nov 2004]. He said late treatment was
the cause of the fatalities, which could have been prevented. "Most of them
were infected by the end of October 2004 but were not treated accordingly,"
Manumpil said.
Measles is a highly contagious respiratory infection caused by the
morbillivirus [i.e. _Measeles virus_, a member of the genus _Morbillivirus_
of the family _Paramyxoviridae_. - Mod.CP]. The disease is common among
children but also seen in older non-immune people. As small children lacked
immunity, without treatment they could die after 3 days of exposure,
Manumpil said.
To prevent the virus from spreading, medical workers had isolated the 3
villages. They were treating sick children with antibiotics, he said. State
Kalabahi Hospital director Yoseph Usen Uma said the children were unlikely
to have been vaccinated against the virus. "Had vaccination taken place
earlier, the impact of the outbreak would not have been that bad," he said.
In most children, measles vaccine is given [in the form of] the
mumps-measles-rubella (MMR) triple immunization. MMR is given twice during
childhood, at the age of 15 months and at 11 to 12 years old. Manumpil said
the virus was airborne and spread through the food and drink consumed by
the children. Alor Regent Ans Takalapeta has ordered medical workers in the
regency to give aid to the survivors. Symptoms of measles include fever, a
hacking cough, runny nose, and a red pimply rash over the body.
[Byline: Yemris Fointuna]
